The generate command, gen, creates new audio of various forms.  Here are
some examples of usage:
 * gen 30 
 Generates 30 seconds of silence.
 * gen 30 sin 
 Generates a 30 second sine wave at 440 Hz.
 * gen 30 sin 1000 
 Generates a 30 second sine wave at 1000 Hz.
 * gen 30 sqw 
 Generates a 30 second square wave at 440 Hz.
 * gen 30 sqw 1000 
Generates a 30 second square wave at 1000 Hz.
And similarly for stw, for sawtooth wave forms. This command has
additional features not yet implemented, but these form a useful starter
set.  Where the frequency is given, a pair of frequencies separated by a
colon may be used, giving a range of frequencies to be swept, as in this:
 * gen 10 sqw 100:6000
The sqw and stw options permit appending a single digit from 1 to 9,
which governs the shape of the square wave or sawtooth wave produced.
For sqw, the digit controls the proportion of positive to negative signal.
The default is 5, for 50%.  For stw, 5 means a symmetrical sawtooth,
and is the default.  A smaller value is a positive sloping sawtooth, and
a higher value is a negative sloping one.  In all cases, the generated
audio will be inserted into the current edit session if a block address
precedes the command name, or will be joined to the end of it otherwise.
